    "summary": "The destruction of Solomon's Temple (586 BC) by Nebuchadnezzar II's Babylonian army was one of the most theologically significant events in Jewish history — the obliteration of the central sanctuary of Israelite religion, the dwelling place of God on earth, and the focal point of the sacrificial cult that defined the religious life of ancient Israel. The Temple, built according to the biblical account by Solomon on Jerusalem's Temple Mount, had stood for approximately 400 years.\n\nThe destruction forced a profound reimagining of Israelite religion. If God had allowed the Temple to be destroyed and the people deported, what did this mean? Prophets like Jeremiah and Ezekiel interpreted the catastrophe as divine punishment for Israel's unfaithfulness to the covenant — but also promised future restoration. The community that survived in exile developed the Torah-centered, synagogue-based religion that became rabbinic Judaism, capable of survival without a homeland or Temple. When a Second Temple was eventually rebuilt (516 BC, by returned exiles under Persian permission), it represented both continuity and a fundamental change: Temple worship was restored, but Judaism had been transformed. The destruction of the Second Temple by Rome in 70 AD (which Orthodox Jews mourn on Tisha B'Av alongside the First Temple's destruction) would complete the transition to the diaspora Judaism that has persisted to the present.",
